SIMPLE: inch
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inch
<hw>Inch</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧nch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gael.
<ets>inis</ets>.]</ety> <def>An island; -- often used in the names of
small islands off the coast of Scotland, <as>as in <ex>Inch</ex>colm,
<ex>Inch</ex>keith, etc.</as></def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inch
<hw>Inch</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>inche</ets>,
<ets>unche</ets>, AS. <ets>ynce</ets>, L. <ets>uncia</ets> the twelfth
part, inch, ounce. See <er>Ounce</er> a weight.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A measure of length, the twelfth part of a foot,
commonly subdivided into halves, quarters, eights, sixteenths, etc., as
among mechanics. It was also formerly divided into twelve parts, called
<xex>lines</xex>, and originally into three parts, called
<xex>barleycorns</xex>, its length supposed to have been determined from
three grains of barley placed end to end lengthwise. It is also
sometimes called a <xex>prime</xex> (⟦prime⟧), composed of twelve
seconds (⟦prime⟧⟦prime⟧), as in the duodecimal system of
arithmetic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note> The symbol ⟦prime⟧ is the same symbol as the light accent, or
the "minutes" of an arc. The "seconds" symbol should actually have the
two strokes closer than in repeated "minutes", but in this dictionary
⟦prime⟧⟦prime⟧ will be interpreted as "seconds".</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>12 seconds (⟦prime⟧⟦prime⟧) make 1 <qex>inch</qex> or prime. 12
<qex>inches</qex> or primes (⟦prime⟧) make 1 foot.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Greenleaf.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The meter, the accepted scientific standard of length,
equals 39.37 inches; the inch is equal to 2.54 centimeters. See
<er>Metric system</er>, and <er>Meter</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small distance or degree, whether of time or
space; hence, a critical moment; also used metaphorically of minor
concessions in bargaining; <as>as, he won't give an <ex>inch</ex>; give
him an <ex>inch</ex> and he'll take a mile</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beldame, I think we watched you at an <qex>inch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>By inches</b></col>, <cd>by slow degrees, gradually.</cd>
-- <col><b>Inch of candle</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Candle</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Inches of pressure</b></col>, <cd>usually, the pressure
indicated by so many inches of a mercury column, as on a steam
gauge.</cd> -- <col><b>Inch of water</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Water</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Miner's inch</b></col>, <fld>(Hydraulic
Mining)</fld>, <cd>a unit for the measurement of water. See <cref>Inch
of water</cref>, under <er>Water</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Inch
<hw>Inch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Inched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inching</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To drive by inches, or small degrees.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He gets too far into the soldier's grace⟦br⟧
And <qex>inches</qex> out my master.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To deal out by inches; to give sparingly.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Inch
<hw>Inch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To advance or retire by inches or
small degrees; to move slowly; <as>as, to <ex>inch</ex>
forward</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With slow paces measures back the field,⟦br⟧
And <qex>inches</qex> to the walls.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Inch
<hw>Inch</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Measuring an inch in any dimension,
whether length, breadth, or thickness; -- used in composition; <as>as, a
two-<ex>inch</ex> cable; a four-<ex>inch</ex> plank.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Inch stuff</b></col>, <cd>boards, etc., sawed one inch
thick.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inchamber</ent>⟦br⟧
